 succeeded in 1366ms:
Analysis summary for ds001_nsclc

I analyzed 50,000 NSCLC records with progression-free survival in months (`pfs_months`) as the continuous outcome. Effect estimates are signed differences or regression coefficients in months of `pfs_months`. The main prognostic model adjusted for age, sex, smoking status, ECOG performance status, histology, stage IV, brain/liver/bone metastases, pleural effusion, albumin, LDH, and 6-month weight loss. Treatment-biomarker models added the relevant treatment, biomarker, and interaction term.

Baseline clinical factors showed the strongest and most consistent associations. Higher `age_years` was unexpectedly associated with longer PFS (+0.16871 months per year, p<1e-300). Poorer `ecog_ps` was strongly adverse (-1.10270 months per point, p<1e-300), as were `stage_iv=1` (-1.41821 months, p<1e-300), `has_brain_mets=1` (-0.91651 months, p<1e-300), squamous histology versus adenocarcinoma (-0.71890 months, p<1e-300), current smoking versus never smoking (-0.39023 months, p=7.80e-240), and `sex_female=1` (-0.20494 months, p=1.39e-178). Former smoking was associated with slightly longer PFS than never smoking (+0.09307 months, p=1.26e-18).

Laboratory and wasting markers behaved mostly as expected. Higher albumin was favorable (+0.45428 months per g/dL, p<1e-300), while higher LDH (-0.00041 months per U/L, p=1.29e-20) and greater 6-month weight loss (-0.07294 months per percentage point, p<1e-300) were adverse. In contrast, liver metastases, bone metastases, and pleural effusion did not add meaningful independent PFS signal once stage, brain metastases, and the other baseline factors were included.

The clearest treatment-biomarker result was for sotorasib and KRAS G12C. A treatment main-effects model showed longer adjusted PFS with `treatment_sotorasib=1` (+0.32405 months, p<1e-300), but the interaction model localized this to `kras_g12c=1`: the `treatment_sotorasib:kras_g12c` interaction was +2.53491 months (p<1e-300), while the sotorasib coefficient among `kras_g12c=0` patients was essentially zero (-0.00068 months, p=0.911). This supports a strong KRAS-specific sotorasib association rather than a broad treatment effect.

Other targeted-treatment hypotheses were not supported. The `treatment_osimertinib:egfr_mutation` interaction was -0.01664 months (p=0.472), and the `treatment_olaparib:brca2_mutation` interaction was -0.00449 months (p=0.923). `brca2_mutation` itself was independently adverse in the biomarker model (-0.11120 months, p=9.54e-9), but there was no evidence that olaparib offset this in BRCA2-mutated patients.

Immunotherapy-marker hypotheses were also refuted. Pembrolizumab benefit was not larger for high PD-L1 (`pdl1_tps>=0.5` interaction +0.00485 months, p=0.781), for `tmb_high=1` (interaction -0.01378 months, p=0.384), or for `stk11_mutation=0` versus `stk11_mutation=1` (interaction -0.01307 months, p=0.515). Continuous `pdl1_tps` was not independently associated with PFS (+0.01261 months per 1.0 increase, p=0.422), and `tmb_high` was not independently associated either (-0.00633 months, p=0.408).

Among residual oncogenic biomarkers, `stk11_mutation` had a small adverse independent association (-0.01998 months, p=0.0323). `alk_fusion` was directionally adverse but narrowly non-significant (-0.03011 months, p=0.0531), and `egfr_mutation` had no independent association (+0.00101 months, p=0.928) after adjustment.

Overall, the dominant signals in this cohort were baseline prognosis, an unexpectedly favorable age association, and a highly specific KRAS G12C-sotorasib interaction. I did not find evidence for pembrolizumab enrichment by PD-L1, TMB, or STK11 status, nor for osimertinib-EGFR or olaparib-BRCA2 interaction effects on `pfs_months` in these data. These are association analyses on the available EHR-derived cohort and should not be read as causal treatment-effect estimates without design assumptions about treatment assignment and censoring.

 succeeded in 1591ms:
Dataset ds001_nsclc: 50000 NSCLC patient records with pfs_months as the continuous outcome. I ran 25 propose-test-refine iterations using adjusted ordinary least-squares models and targeted subgroup mean comparisons. Adjusted models included demographics, stage, brain metastases, albumin, LDH, weight loss, CRP, NLR, ECOG performance status, histology, smoking, treatments, and key biomarkers unless otherwise noted.

The strongest general prognostic signals were clinical status and disease burden. Older age was unexpectedly associated with longer PFS: 1.684 months per 10-year higher age_years (p=0.000). In contrast, stage IV disease (-1.417 months, p=0.000), ECOG 2 versus 0 (-2.177 months, p=0.000), brain metastases (-0.912 months, p=0.000), squamous histology (-0.723 months, p=0.000), current versus never smoking (-0.545 months, p=0.000), and sex_female (-0.203 months, p=0.000) were all independently associated with shorter PFS.

Nutritional and tumor-burden laboratory features also tracked PFS. Each 1 percentage-point higher weight_loss_pct_6mo had a -0.073 month coefficient for PFS (p=0.000), each 1 g/dL higher albumin_g_dl had a 0.463 month coefficient (p=0.000), and each 100 U/L higher ldh_u_l had a -0.045 month coefficient (p=0.000).

The clearest treatment signal was biomarker-specific sotorasib benefit. The adjusted sotorasib main effect was 0.323 months (p=0.000), and the treatment_sotorasib by kras_g12c interaction was large and positive: 2.533 months (p=0.000). In the KRAS G12C subgroup, mean PFS was 2.552 months higher with sotorasib (p=0.000), while the KRAS G12C-negative subgroup showed no benefit (-0.005 months, p=0.799). Additional sotorasib interactions were negative for egfr_mutation (-0.208 months, p=0.000), alk_fusion (-0.343 months, p=0.000), and brca2_mutation (-0.328 months, p=0.000), with a smaller positive interaction for tmb_high (0.076 months, p=5.40e-7).

Several plausible biomarker and treatment hypotheses were not supported. stk11_mutation was only weakly adverse (-0.019 months, p=0.037), and brca2_mutation was independently adverse (-0.109 months, p=8.16e-9). However, pembrolizumab had no positive adjusted association (-0.006 months, p=0.383), pdl1_tps had no meaningful main effect (0.003 months per 0.50 higher value, p=0.668), and the pembrolizumab by pdl1_tps interaction was null (0.004 months, p=0.781). Similarly, there was no evidence of biomarker-concordant benefit for osimertinib in egfr_mutation (-0.020 interaction months, p=0.335) or olaparib in brca2_mutation (-0.004 interaction months, p=0.930).

Overall, this cohort showed strong prognostic structure and one dominant predictive treatment interaction: sotorasib benefit was concentrated in KRAS G12C-positive disease. The evidence did not support the expected pembrolizumab-PD-L1, osimertinib-EGFR, or olaparib-BRCA2 benefit patterns in this dataset. The age and sex findings are notable because their directions are not the usual clinical expectation, so they should be treated as dataset-specific associations rather than causal conclusions.

 succeeded in 1796ms:
Oncology dataset analysis summary for ds001_nsclc

I analyzed 50000 NSCLC patient records with no missing values in the decoded Parquet file. The outcome was pfs_months, modeled as a continuous endpoint. Analyses used unadjusted mean comparisons for direct subgroup contrasts and ordinary least-squares models for multivariable main-effect and interaction tests; signed estimates are in months of progression-free survival.

Iteration narrative

- Iteration 1 tested unadjusted treatment main effects. Sotorasib showed a clear positive association; pembrolizumab, olaparib, and osimertinib did not show significant unselected benefit.
- Iteration 2 evaluated immunotherapy-adjacent biomarkers. Neither PD-L1 TPS nor TMB-high was significant in the adjusted model.
- Iteration 3 refined immunotherapy hypotheses. Neither pembrolizumab-by-PD-L1 nor pembrolizumab-by-TMB showed significant positive modification.
- Iteration 4 tested STK11 mutation as an adverse marker and pembrolizumab modifier; neither effect was significant in the adjusted model.
- Iteration 5 identified a strong KRAS G12C-specific sotorasib benefit.
- Iteration 6 tested whether STK11 modified sotorasib benefit within KRAS G12C disease.
- Iteration 7 tested EGFR-specific osimertinib benefit; neither the adjusted interaction nor the EGFR-mutant subgroup comparison supported benefit.
- Iteration 8 tested brain metastases as an osimertinib modifier within EGFR-mutant disease; there was no significant interaction.
- Iteration 9 tested BRCA2-specific olaparib benefit; neither the adjusted interaction nor BRCA2-mutant subgroup comparison supported benefit.
- Iteration 10 screened ALK and ROS1 fusions; neither reached conventional significance in the adjusted model.
- Iteration 11 screened MET exon14 skipping and HER2 amplification; neither showed a significant adjusted association.
- Iteration 12 screened RET fusion and EGFR mutation main effects; neither was independently significant in this adjusted specification.
- Iteration 13 confirmed older age as favorable, female sex as adverse, and ECOG performance status and stage IV disease as strongly adverse clinical factors.
- Iteration 14 found brain metastases were strongly adverse, while liver metastases were not significant after adjustment.
- Iteration 15 found recent weight loss was strongly adverse, while bone metastases were not significant after adjustment.
- Iteration 16 confirmed albumin was favorable while LDH was adverse.
- Iteration 17 tested CRP and NLR; neither was significant after adjustment.
- Iteration 18 found squamous histology and current smoking were adverse.
- Iteration 19 tested hemoglobin and alkaline phosphatase; neither was significant after adjustment.
- Iteration 20 tested sodium and calcium; neither was significant after adjustment.
- Iteration 21 tested COPD and chronic kidney disease; neither was significant after adjustment.
- Iteration 22 tested autoimmune disease as an immunotherapy modifier; the interaction was small and not convincingly significant.
- Iteration 23 found heart failure was adverse, while interstitial lung disease history was not significant.
- Iteration 24 retested the pembrolizumab-by-PD-L1 pattern with a median split; the interaction was not significant.
- Iteration 25 pooled biomarker-matched targeted therapy across EGFR, KRAS G12C, and BRCA2-positive patients; the matched indicator was strongly positive, largely consistent with the KRAS G12C/sotorasib signal.

